sql:
SELECT resource_type, resource_description
FROM resource_types
ORDER BY resource_type;

external_knowledge:
- "Effective improvements" refer to those with the highest resource multipliers for each resource type;
- "Resource multiplier" is a factor that increases the production rate of a resource;
- "Discovery probability" is the likelihood of discovering a resource when the improvement is applied;
- "Base yield" is the amount of resource produced without any multipliers;
- "Trade value" is the value of the resource in trade;
- "Maximum quantity" is the maximum amount of the resource that can be produced by the improvement.

- "Enhanced yield" is calculated by multiplying the base yield by (1 + resource multiplier);
- "Valid improvements" are those that make the resource valid for use;
- "Tradeable improvements" are those that allow the resource to be traded.

- "Improvement types" refer to different kinds of infrastructure or enhancements in a game or simulation, such as farms and mines;
- "Total production value" is the combined output of resources produced by an improvement, calculated by multiplying the resource multiplier with the base yield;
- "Resource costs," "build times," "maintenance costs," "maximum quantities," "resource multipliers," and "discovery probabilities" are all factors that influence the efficiency and effectiveness of an improvement.

- "resource_trade = 1" indicates that the resource is tradable.;
- "improvement_type" refers to the type of improvement, such as a farm or mine.;
- "resource_type" refers to the type of resource, such as wheat or iron.

- The `resource_multiplier` is a factor that enhances the production rate of a resource when applied to an improvement;
- The `resource_makes_valid` field is a boolean indicating whether the improvement can be used with the resource;
- The `yield_increase_percentage` is calculated as the percentage increase from the base yield to the improved yield.

- "Valid resources" are those that can be produced by an improvement;
- "Tradeable resources" are those that can be traded;
- "Discovery probability" refers to the likelihood of finding a resource if it has a random discovery requirement;
- "Total resource cost" is the sum of the costs to build the improvements that affect the resource;
- "Average build time" and "average maintenance cost" are the mean times and costs for building and maintaining the improvements.

- "Highly discoverable" refers to a resource discovery probability greater than 0.7;
- "High maintenance cost" refers to an improvement maintenance cost greater than 5;
- "Valid improvements" are those where `resource_makes_valid` is 1.
